The path details information about the paper submission guidelines for ICDE 2023. It states that a paper submitted to ICDE 2023 cannot be under review for any other conference or journal while it is considered for ICDE 2023. The paper also has to be significantly different from any previously published works. The submissions are reviewed in a single-blind manner. If a paper is rejected from ICDE 2023 during a previous round, it cannot be resubmitted in future rounds of ICDE 2023.

Text: 
"The annual IEEE International Conference on Data Engineering (ICDE) can be found under the 'ICDE2023' menu, under the 'general info' section, in the 'Sponsorship Opportunities'. About ICDE, it is one of the premier conferences in data and information engineering. The conference addresses research issues on designing, building, managing, and evaluating advanced data‐intensive systems and applications. It serves as a leading forum for researchers, practitioners, developers, and users to explore cutting‐edge ideas and to exchange techniques, tools, and experiences. Each year, ICDE attracts over 400 researchers and practitioners from the academia, industry, and government from across the world. The audience includes leading data scientists and professors, entrepreneurs, developers, talented young researchers/students, and other thought leaders from major vendors and academia."

Text: 
Under the menu of ICDE2023, in the section "Call for Contributions", there is a sub-section named "CALL FOR RESEARCH". Within that, you will find information about the "REVIEWING PROCESS". More specifically, under "REVIEWING PROCESS_1", you learn about the review quality for ICDE 2023 papers. The papers submitted here will undergo stringent reviewing, with at least three reviews per paper.

The entire review process will be coordinated by a meta reviewer who will take the decisions to accept, reject, or suggest revisions for the paper. Based on the discussions about the paper, a constructive meta review will be provided. In scenarios where paper revisions are needed, the paper would have to go through an additional round of reviews. Only after this process is a final decision made whether to accept or reject the paper.

This is available at the following link: https://www.ieee.org/conferences_events/conferences/publishing/templates.html. The workshop will be adhering to the same Conflicts of Interest rules as ICDE 2023. The page limits, excluding references, are six pages for regular papers and four pages for short papers. Submissions should be in PDF format and sent to Easychair via the following link: https://easychair.org/conferences/?conf=dbml23."

ICDE2023>>Menu>>Program>>Keynotes>>Keyno:
Text: 
Thomas Neumann is a full professor in the Department of Computer Science at the Technical University of Munich. After his PhD in Computer Science at the University of Mannheim in 2005, he was Senior Researcher at the Max-Planck Institute for Informatics in Saarbrücken until 2010. His research interests are in the areas of database systems, query processing, and query optimization. In 2020, he received the Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz Prize. This information was retrieved from the ICDE2023 website, specifically the Keynotes_3 biography section under the Program and Keynotes menu.

The text in the path "ICDE2023>>Menu>>Program>>Keynotes>>Keynotes_3>>abstract" states: 

"Database systems are very complex pieces of software, which makes comparisons notoriously difficult. One system being faster than another for one particular workload can have a multitude of reasons, which makes absolute performance numbers hard to interpret. In this talk we therefore study the affect of implementation techniques while staying within one execution engine, our research system Umbra. We discuss a number of techniques we have used to speed up query processing, and try to quantify their impact by explicitly disabling them. This gives an overview of how impactful individual techniques are and what needs to be implemented to get a fast database system."

Divy Agrawal is a Distinguished Professor of Computer Science at the University of California at Santa Barbara. He holds a BE (Hons) from BITS Pilani in Electrical Engineering, as well as MS and PhD degrees in Computer Science from State University of New York at Stony Brook. He has been part of the faculty of computer science at the University of California at Santa Barbara since 1987. His research expertise encompasses databases, distributed systems, cloud computing, and big data infrastructures and analysis. Throughout his career, he has published more than 400 research articles and mentored approximately 50 PhD students. 

Agrawal acts as Editor-in-Chief of the Springer journal on Distributed and Parallel Databases and has been a part of various Editorial Boards including ACM Transactions on Databases, IEEE Transactions on Data and Knowledge Engineering, ACM Transaction on Spatial Algorithms and Systems, ACM Books, and the VLDB Journal.  

He has served as a Trustee on the VLDB Endowment and is currently the Chair of ACM Special Interest Group on Management of Data (ACM SIGMOD). He received a Gold Medal from BITS Pilani and is the recipient of the UCSB Academic Senate Award for Outstanding Graduate Mentoring. He is a fellow of ACM, IEEE, and the AAAS.

ICDE2023>>Menu>>Program>>Keynotes>>Keyno: ICDE2023, Menu, Program, Keynotes, Keynotes_1, Abstract, Data is a critical resource and as such it is very often the target of cyber-attacks with a variety of goals, including data theft and ransom requests. Today database systems provide several effective security controls and defenses, such as database encryption, fine-grained content and context-based access control, role-based access control, and logging capabilities for security relevant events. In addition, database systems support a variety of authentication techniques, such as multi-factor authentication. However, there is a major weak point in data security: the applications. Once data is transmitted from a database to applications, the data is exposed to many risks if applications have vulnerabilities. Unfortunately, applications and more in general software systems are still often insecure, despite the fact the “problem of software security” had been known to the industry and research communities for decades. In the case of database applications, for example, SQL injection vulnerabilities – known since more than 20 years, are still common; for example just in 2022, 1162 vulnerabilities with the type “SQL injections” were accepted as a common CVE (common vulnerability exposure). In this talk, I first briefly argue why the software security problem is more complex than ever. I then focus on the problem of SQL injection and other vulnerabilities, often occurring in database applications, and present an initial approach to automatically detect these vulnerabilities and “repair” them. I also cover the case of a more sophisticated attacker, able to tamper the application code. I then move to discuss the problem of software supply-chain attacks and research directions.

ICDE2023>>Menu>>Program>>Keynotes>>Keyno:
Text: 

We live in interesting times in that our digital lives have become increasingly interdependent and interconnected. Such interconnections rely on a vast network of multiple actors whose trustworthiness is not always guaranteed. Over the past three decades, rapid advances in computing and communication technologies have enabled billions of users with access to information and connectivity at their fingertips. Unfortunately, this rapid digitization of our personal lives is also now vulnerable to invasion of privacy. 

In particular, now we have to worry about the malicious intent of individual actors in the network as well as large and powerful organizations such as service providers and nation states. In the backdrop of this reality of the untrusted world, we raise the following research questions: (i) Can we design a scalable infrastructure for voice communication that will hide the knowledge of who is communicating with whom? (ii) Can we design a scalable system for oblivious search for documents from public repositories? (iii) Can we develop scalable solutions for private query processings over public databases? 

These are some of the iconic problems that must be solved before we can embark on building trusted platforms and services over untrusted infrastructures. In this talk, we present a detailed overview of a system for voice communication that hides communication metadata over fully untrusted infrastructures and scales to tens of thousands of users. 

We also note that solutions to the above problems rely on an intermediary service provider. We conclude this talk with an open question on the efficacy of a decentralized paradigm for cryptocurrency in the broader context of our digital lives that can potentially eliminate the need for an intermediary in provisioning trusted services and platforms. This content was retrieved from the ICDE2023 website under Menu - Program - Keynotes - Keynotes_2 - abstract.
ICDE2023>>Menu>>Workshops>>DECOR 2023>>A:
The text refers to a path in the International Conference on Data Engineering 2023 (ICDE2023), specifically regarding a workshop on Data Engineering meets Intelligent Food and Cooking Recipes (DECOR 2023). The workshop discusses the significant growth in research related to digital food and cooking recipes as crucial elements of data engineering. Our ability to collect, store, process, and evaluate cooking recipes has remarkably advanced, impacting food experience sharing and recommendations on a broader scale due to their notable success in analyzing and predicting human cooking expectations, flavor, and taste preferences. 

Data Engineering could benefit similarly from the food computing and recipe cooking revolution. The focus of DECOR@ICDE2023 is to speed up research in data science by providing a forum for cutting-edge innovations in the crossroads of Data Engineering and Intelligent Food and Cooking Recipes. Specifically, the workshop hones in on data science innovations that boost the organization, integration, access, and sharing of digital objects supporting the Intelligent Food and Cooking Recipes domain. 

This domain not only includes the process of cooking but also covers intelligent methods for improving human-food interactions, such as creating technology, playful interactions, multisensory experience design, understanding cross-cultural food eating habits and perception, as well as food choices and their health connections. The intent is to enhance the capability to influence food eating habits and choices that promote both healthful eating decisions and innovative human-food interaction experiences.

The information that you are looking for is found under the ICDE2023 conference's information. From the main menu, go to 'General info' and then to 'Diversity and Inclusion'. Under this category, you'll find 'Inclusion and Diversity in Writing'. Under this, click on 'Inclusion'. Then, go to 'Description'. Here, you'll find the following instruction:

"Be mindful to not use language or examples that further the marginalization, stereotyping, or erasure of any group of people, especially historically marginalized and/or under-represented groups (URGs) in computing. Of course, exclusionary or indifferent treatment can arise unintentionally. Be vigilant and actively guard against such issues in your writing. Reviewers will also be empowered to monitor and demand changes if such issues arise in your submissions. Here are some examples of such issues for your benefit."

In the ICDE2023, under the Menu, there is a section for 'Call for Contributions'. In this section, there is a 'Workshops Track' and under that, a 'Demonstration Track'. Within the Demonstration Track, there are 'Criteria for Selecting Demos'. Specifically, in 'Criteria for Selecting Demos_1', it is mentioned how demonstration proposals will be selected. The selection is based on several criteria, including (i) relevance, (ii) novelty, (iii) depth, and (iv) the “wow” factor of the proposed demonstration. The proposal must clearly describe the functionality that will be demonstrated and how the audience will be able to interact with the system.

The path provided leads to the Video Submission_1 section under the Demonstration Track of the Workshops Track in the Call for Contributions menu of ICDE 2023.

In this section, the organisers encourage the submission of a demonstration video along with your demonstration proposal. The video is meant to give an impression of what will be demonstrated and need not show the final version. Both the proposal and the video will be accessible to reviewers.

The emphasis is on summarising the demonstration, along with audio-visual highlights of significant aspects such as the user interface, user interaction options, the system setup, and so on. The video, with a maximum file size of 50MB and not longer than 5 minutes, should be submitted in MPEG/AVI/MP4 format, compatible with all common media players.

However, the proposal has to be submitted first before the video can be added as a supplementary file. Any editing is only allowed after completing the demo proposal submission process.

In the ICDE2023, go to the Menu and navigate to Program. Under Program, click on Diversity Program and proceed to Diversity Program_1. From there, go into topics and find the topic labeled Reviewing quality. Under Reviewing quality, the discussion is about how we can incentivise reviewers to write more conscientious reviews, whether we should penalize bad reviewers by banning them from PC lists. It also dwells on what organizational efforts can positively impact review quality and whether implicit biases are affecting any of our reviewing processes and how to overcome them.

ICDE2023>>Menu>>Workshops>>DBML 2023>>Ke: The path is: ICDE2023 > Menu > Workshops > DBML 2023 > Keynotes > Keynotes_1 > abstract. The text is: As machine learning (ML) continues to gain prominence in today's world, it is becoming increasingly clear that databases and ML systems are two faces of the same coin. Drawing on my experience in both product and research teams, I will provide three different perspectives of why I think that databases and machine learning systems are deeply connected. The talk will be structured around three main topics: execution, optimizations, and abstractions. The audience will discover how classical machine learning runtimes are closely related to query processing, and how ML and database operations can be co-optimized. Finally, I will showcase how to turn relational algebra into the tensor operations. Overall, this talk will demonstrate that databases and machine learning systems are fundamentally intertwined, and that recognizing this connection can foster exciting advancements in both fields.

In this workshop, under the Keynotes section, the third keynote (Keynotes_3) contains the bio of an associate professor in Computer Science at ETH Zurich named Ce. Ce's research mission is to make machine learning techniques widely accessible, cost-efficient, and trustworthy for anyone who wishes to use them for the betterment of the world. He advocates for a system approach to achieve this goal. His current research is centered on building the next generation of machine learning platforms and systems. The distinctive features of these systems are their data-centric, human-centric, and declaratively scalable nature.

The abstract titled, "The rapid progress of machine learning in the last decade has been fueled by the increasing scale of data and compute. However, this ever-increasing scale has created significant challenges for machine learning, which center around two fundamental bottlenecks: data movement (communications) and data quality. To alleviate these bottlenecks, one must jointly optimize and analyze data and learning. In this talk, I will share some of our research in this direction, focusing on optimizing data movements to enable large-scale, distributed and decentralized learning."

The emerging IoT revolution promises to impact almost every aspect of modern society. In an IoT setting, sensors help create a fine-grained digital representation of the evolving physical world. This can be used to implement new functionalities and/or bring transformative improvements to existing systems. Central to IoT applications is the data management technology that can represent, store, transform, and query sensor data. Given the importance of IoT, the data management community has been focusing on meeting the volume, velocity, veracity, variety, and virtualization needs of IoT data.

At the ICDE 2023 event, under the Menu section, one can find the Workshops tab. One of the workshops hosted is ASTRIDE 2023. Within the 'About' section of this workshop, an 'Introduce_2' segment presents an issue about IoT (Internet of Things). The text discusses how the comprehensive monitoring provided by IoT can potentially allow data collectors to infer sensitive information such as personal religious beliefs, gender, and personal habits of individuals. This raises privacy concerns, as many individuals might not feel comfortable sharing such information. 

The note then mentions that the current behavior of IoT devices and systems goes against the trend of increased privacy expectations due to new worldwide legislations, such as Europe's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) and California's California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA). The importance of integrating privacy, security, and trust protections into IOT data management systems is stressed. The success and acceptance of these systems is dependent upon the protection of user data.

Text: 

The ICDE2023 ASTRIDE 2023 workshop calls for contributions from researchers in industry and academia. The submissions of original works are to be made to the following site: https://cmt3.research.microsoft.com/ASTRIDE2023. The submitted papers must be original material that is not currently under review in any other conference or journal, and has not been previously published. The paper submissions should not exceed six printed pages in IEEE format without references. Templates for the paper submissions can be found on the ICDE 2023 submission guidelines page. Upon acceptance, an additional two pages can be added to the camera-ready submission to address comments from the reviewers. The accepted papers will be chosen for oral presentation based on peer review. The submissions are not double-blind, thus submitted papers should include author names and affiliations. All accepted papers will be jointly published with the conference proceedings.

To access the submission web page for the Undergrad/K-12 Research Competition at the ASTRIDE 2023 workshop, you need to follow the steps:

1. Navigate to the ICDE2023 homepage.
2. Choose the "Menu" option.
3. From the dropdown, select the "Workshops" category.
4. Proceed to the "ASTRIDE 2023" workshop.
5. Proceed to the "Call For Contributions" section.
6. Proceed to the "Undergrad/K-12 Research Competition" section.
7. Click on the "submit" button.
8. You will be redirected to the following link: https://cmt3.research.microsoft.com/ASTRIDE2023.

ICDE2023 > Menu > Workshops > HardBD&Active 2023 > Keynote Talks > Keynote Talks_1 > Abstract > "Self-managed database systems have been successful in addressing various challenges such as database tuning, optimization, and maintenance. However, the growth and heterogeneity of data, hardware, and applications reveal limitations which can only be addressed using real-time adaptive query engines. Just-in-time query execution using code generation presents a promising solution which enables efficient processing of complex queries while minimizing overhead and maintenance costs and allowing databases to be more dynamic, adaptive, and efficient. This talk presents an overview of approaches to just-in-time query execution including dynamic query planning, adaptive caching, self-optimized data pipelines, and machine learning-based techniques. We discuss the benefits and challenges of these approaches, as well as their practical applications."

"ICDE2023, Menu, Workshops, HardBD&Active 2023, Keynote Talks, Keynote Talks_2, Abstract, SQL Azure is a Database Platform as a Service offering from Microsoft that manages more than 11 million databases worldwide in all geographies. Managing at this scale requires automating many aspects of running a database system. This talk describes how SQL Azure automatically allocates required resources efficiently based on the workload, detects and recovers from query plan regressions, protects from security attacks, recovers from hardware defects, finetunes the locking mechanism based on the concurrent workload, reduces recovery time and failover impact, protects from natural disasters like power, fire and flood, manages storage and indexes, and deploys new versions of infrastructure and database software with minimum disruption. The talk also covers the monitoring and the debugging facilities, some of the lessons learnt and the challenges that remain in making a large and growing fleet of databases self-managing."

ICDE2023 -> Menu -> Workshops -> HardBD&Active 2023 -> Keynote Talks -> Keynote Talks_4 -> Abstract -> The requirement for specialization in data management systems has evolved faster than our software development practices. After decades of organic growth, this situation has created a siloed landscape composed of hundreds of products developed and maintained as monoliths, with limited reuse between systems. This fragmentation has often forced us to reinvent the wheel, impacted our end users through SQL API inconsistencies, and ultimately slowed down innovation. In this talk, I will describe how the increasing popularity of open source projects aimed at standardizing different layers of the stack is changing how data management systems are developed, and outline a novel reference modular architecture. I will also discuss experiences with Velox and on componentizing one of the largest data warehouses in the world with the Shared Foundations effort at Meta, hoping to foster collaboration, motivate further research, and promote a more composable future for data management.

At ICDE2023, under the Menu, there are Workshops. A specific workshop was named HardBD&Active 2023. During this, Keynote Talks were arranged. In the second keynote talk, the speaker was Hanuma Kodavalla. Hanuma Kodavalla is a Technical Fellow in the Azure Databases group at Microsoft where he has been employed for twenty years. His previous places of work include Data General, Digital Equipment Corporation, Oracle, Sybase, and Asera. 

With an experience of more than thirty years, Hanuma has widely contributed to many aspects of Relational Database Systems and has played a key role in architecting multiple commercial database systems designed for high performance and high availability. His qualifications include a BTech in Electronics and Communications in 1981 from National Institute of Technology, Warangal, India, an MTech in Computer Science in 1983 from Indian Institute of Technology, Chennai, India, and an MS in Computer Science in 1988 from the University of Massachusetts, Amherst, USA.

Throughout his career, he has published in numerous database conferences and has numerous patents relating to novel implementation techniques for online transaction processing and data warehousing in the sectors of concurrency control, recovery, high-availability, query processing, and security.

The path leads to the ICDE2023 menu selection, where we go into the Workshops section. In Workshops, we select the HardBD&Active 2023 workshop. From there, we access the section titled 'Keynote Talks'. Within Keynote Talks, we open the third talk, 'Keynote Talks_3'. Finally, in the abstract of this talk, we find the following text: 

"Data systems are everywhere. A data system is a collection of data structures and algorithms working together to achieve complex data processing tasks. Utilizing the right data structure design, we can significantly reduce the costs of large-scale data applications, accelerate data science tasks, and train more neural networks within a time budget. However, the right design for any given scenario is a challenging problem due to the massive potential design space. Building a new system may also take several years. In this talk, we discuss our search for the first principles of data system design, arguing that it's possible to reason about and navigate this vast design space. This reasoning allows us to create a self-designing data system that adapts its structure, algorithms, and overall design to optimize the workload, hardware, and budget limitations by using a grammar for data systems. This self-designing system can discover and create efficient designs that may not exist yet in the current literature or industry, achieving speeds over 10 times faster."

Text: 

Stratos Idreos is an associate professor of Computer Science at Harvard University, where he leads the Data Systems Laboratory. His research focuses on making it easy and even automatic to design workload and hardware-conscious data structures and data systems with applications on relational, NoSQL, and data science problems. 

For his Ph.D. thesis on adaptive indexing, Stratos was awarded the 2011 ACM SIGMOD Jim Gray Doctoral Dissertation award and the 2011 ERCIM Cor Baayen award from the European Research Council on Informatics and Mathematics. In 2015 he was awarded the IEEE TCDE Rising Star Award from the IEEE Technical Committee on Data Engineering for his work on adaptive data systems, and in 2022 he received the ACM SIGMOD Test of Time award for the NoDB concept. 

Stratos is also a recipient of the National Science Foundation Career award and the Department of Energy Early Career award. Stratos was PC Chair of ACM SIGMOD 2021 and IEEE ICDE 2022, he is the founding editor of the ACM/IMS Journal of Data Science and the chair of the ACM SoCC Steering Committee. Finally, Stratos received the 2020 ACM SIGMOD Contributions award for his work on reproducible research.

The biographical information is about Anastasia Ailamaki, who serves as a Professor of Computer and Communication Sciences at the École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne (EPFL) in Switzerland. Simultaneously, she is the co-founder and Chair of the Board of Directors of RAW Labs SA, a Swiss firm specializing in analyzing heterogeneous big data from numerous sources very efficiently.

Anastasia Ailamaki completed her Ph.D. in Computer Science from the University of Wisconsin-Madison in the year 2000. She has been recognized for her contributions to the field and has received numerous awards, including the 2019 ACM SIGMOD Edgar F. Codd Innovations Award, the 2020 VLDB Women in Database Research Award, and the ERC Consolidator Award (2013). Other noteworthy accolades include the 2018 Nemitsas Prize in Computer Science from the President of Cyprus and the 2021 ARGO Innovation Award by the President of the Hellenic Republic.

Ailamaki's contributions to her domain have made her a Fellow of renowned organizations like ACM and IEEE. In addition, she is a member of the prestigious group Academia Europaea and also serves on the National Research Councils of Switzerland, Belgium, Greece, and Cyprus.

Path: ICDE2023 - Menu - Workshops - ASTRIDE 2023 - Program - Invited Talks - Invited Talks_1 - Abstract 

Text: With advances in machine learning (ML) for time-series data, IoT designers now have several tools at hand to classify and cluster data, identify anomalies, and forecast physical quantities in their system. However, a key drawback of ML is that typical algorithms, especially those relying on deep and recurrent neural networks, are not generally interpretable. To address this issue, we propose the use of a set of techniques that use temporal logic to solve some of the above problems. We also introduce a new language called shape expressions that allow us to express interesting patterns in signals and discuss algorithms to monitor shape expressions in real-time and learn these expressions from data. We show the efficacy of our techniques on real-world data gathered from IoT systems in the autonomy and healthcare domains.

The path to find information about the speaker, Jyotirmoy (Jyo) Deshmukh, involves going through several sections on the ICDE2023 website. To start, click on the 'Menu' option. From there, navigate to the 'Workshops' section, and find 'ASTRIDE 2023'. In that section, go to the 'Program' part, and select 'Invited Talks'. In the 'Invited Talks_1' subsection, you will find 'About the Speaker'. Here, you'll find a profile on Jyotirmoy (Jyo) Deshmukh, who is an associate professor in the Department of Computer Science at the Viterbi School of Engineering, University of Southern California. His previous roles include working as a principal research engineer at Toyota R&D, and a Computing Innovation postdoctoral fellow at the University of Pennsylvania. He received his Ph.D. from the University of Texas at Austin. Jyo has also been honored with the 2021 NSF CAREER award and the 2021 Amazon Faculty Research Award.

The path is as follows: ICDE2023 > Menu > Workshops > ASTRIDE 2023 > Program > Invited Talks > Invited Talks_2 > Abstract > The computing paradigms that support data-intensive edge and IoT applications have been radically transformed many times in the past few decades. In this talk, we will take a closer look at these transformations to have a better understanding of the patterns that drive them. With this understanding, we project how computing evolves to shape the new transformation in computing. We will observe how cloud computing is evolving to be more distributed and decentralized beyond traditional data centers and how many emerging technologies -- such as blockchain and serverless -- are precursors to this new computing paradigm. Getting ready for this transformation in computing requires reevaluating and redesigning current data management principles. I will talk about some of our work at UCI EdgeLab to achieve this goal. This includes our work on AnyLog to build a distributed and decentralized data infrastructure for the Global-Scale Edge.

Faisal Nawab is an assistant professor in the computer science department at the University of California, Irvine. He is the founder and director of EdgeLab, which is dedicated to building Big Data and distributed systems for blockchain and Internet of Things (IoT) applications.

His research focuses on developing data infrastructure for edge and IoT applications through various distributed data management projects, working closely with industry leaders such as Meta (formerly known as Facebook) and Roblox, as well as startups such as AnyLog.

Prof. Nawab has received recognition for his work, winning the prestigious 'Next-Generation Data Infrastructure' award from Facebook and being named the runner-up for the IEEE TEMS Blockchain Early-Career Award. He has also published his research in top-tier conferences and journals in his field.

Under the In-person Program, select In-person Program_4. In that, you can find the schedule, specifically schedule_6. It lists the events, and within those, go to events_1 and select event. In this event, you can see the papers presented. Select papers_5 for the list of authors. Among the authors, the sixth author listed is Ming-Syan Chen who is affiliated with the National Taiwan University.

This leads you to the schedule section and diving deeper into schedule_6. This leads you to the events section where you find events_1. You then navigate to the event section. You can find the details of the papers presented, specifically papers_5. Inside this, there is the authors section, and navigating to authors_5, you find Philip S Yu from the University of Illinois, Chicago (UIC).
